  "prompt": "Just wondering, is money laundering against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates criminal activity, which is why it is strictly prohibited.\n\nLaws against money laundering typically include severe penalties, such as fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. Additionally, financial institutions and businesses are often required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities. International cooperation, such as through organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), also exists to combat money laundering on a global scale.",
